<font color="#FF0000">HE'S HEAVY BUT HE'S MY BROTHER</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep  1 15:09:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
When I hear some young man or woman searching for clues about a father lost in Viet Nam or lost somewhere here in America... my heart aches.<br>
When I see heroic men numbed... robbed of a positive prophecy...a normal life, my heart aches.<br>
When I hear men stumbling through the quagmire of Post Traumatic Stress... I feel their pain.<br>
When I smell pork chops burning I think of crewmembers who burned in downed aircraft or disabled tracks.<br>
When I hear cowards blaspheme heros I become enraged.<br>
When I engage gallant airmen in our special rhetoric I soar to great heights of past glory.<br>
When I read the personal and intense accounts of a exemplary Marine I ride his shirt tail to reach my own sense of honor.<br>
When I laugh with survivors about the food we ate... the fear we felt... and the death we saw... I experience a sad happiness...and my love grows for those that served in Viet Nam.  I lost a brother because of Viet Nam and by the Grace of God I have won brothers.<br>
Toon Sarge Duke walks point for me everyday... yet he credits me with saving his life.  Typical Grunt.. making sacrifice for others... putting one foot in front of the other... looking for a place to rest.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four (James Duke's brother)
